<lb corresp="#b2"/><w><supplied>naṣ</supplied></w><w><supplied>u</supplied>pacār</w><w>pätāñäkte</w><w>anapär</w><w>śāñcapo</w><w>nesset</w><w>yal</w><num value="21">20-1</num><w>ke</w><w>ñomā</w><w>ne</w>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><w><supplied>yāme</supplied>ñc</w><w>cami</w><w>yälya</w><w>tkanā</w><w>knāl</w><w>cam</w><w>ṣñi</w><w>waṣtäṣ</w><w>lutseñc-äṃ</w><pc>:</pc><w>kuppren<supplied>e</supplied></w>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="2"/><w><supplied>tsä</supplied>knātsi</w><w>kri</w><w>naṣ-äṃ</w><w>kutkäryaṣ</w><w>omälyāṃ</w><w>ṣpal</w><w>musnāl</w><w>tsaryo</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">The one to whom ones gives ... to eat or to drink, this one becomes under ones control. With that one </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... sesame,  mung bean, long pepper, cassia fistula, Dalbergia sissoo. As much as </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">everything is (available), as much indeed a single (person) pours it in ...-wise. One should mix together all these (ingredients). To whom      </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">one gives that in the food or in the drink, this one becomes insane. If to return with the mind </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">one wishes, one should make a recitation (?) with milk containing sugar. It is good for him. Of the Daśamālā-sūtra</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">this is the treatment. In front of the Buddha (statue) one should cast a spell on the Dalbergia sissoo 21. In whose name    </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">they make [it], the (Dalbergia sissoo) has to be strewn over the earth that is expected to be walked on by him. [Then] they expel him from his own house. In case that</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">one has the wish to pull out (a spike?) one should rise a hot pill from ... with the hand.   </seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">This is an almost complete leaf with few akṣaras missing on the left side. By comparison with the lines of the leaf <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns1"/> there is one - maximal two - akṣaras missing at the beginning of the lines a3 and a4, b1 and b2. The general disposition is worse than in the leaf <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns1"/>. There are traces of horizontal ruling, but there is no place reserved for the string hole which is between lines 2 and 3. The script is less formal than in the average TA manuscripts. Recto and verso can not be securely ascertained because of the absence of a leaf number at the left margin. On the recto side there many traces of imprints from akṣaras of another leaf.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="lingcomment">The form <hi>taṃpar</hi> seems to be an adverb comparable to <hi>keṃ-par</hi> 'perversely' based on a noun <hi>taṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">The segmentation after the verb <hi>kuṣ</hi> is not entirely certain.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="lingcomment">The word <hi>pār</hi> can be identified with TB <hi>pār</hi> 'recitation', a loan from Skt. <hi>pātha-</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
